{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515369"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:31:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:31:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12445"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12445"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.05,0.26,0.63,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4953"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102443"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4953"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84917"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45968"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102443"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 49-year-old woman presents to the emergency department (ED) of a tertiary centre with a three day history of persistent right upper quadrant abdominal pain. She has experienced two episodes of vomiting. Her medical history is includes well-controlled diabetes and osteoarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 118/80 mmHg, pulse 92/min, temperature 36.8\u00a0\u00b0C and respiratory rate 16/min. She is tender in the right upper quadrant of her abdomen and there are no other abnormal physical signs. An abdominal ultrasound shows shows gallstones, a thickened gallbladder and some dilatation of her common bile duct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer laboratory tests are shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations would be most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatobiliary scintigraphy (HIDA scan)","Computer tomography (CT) scan of the abdomen","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","Endoscopic ultrasonography (EUS)"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s clinical picture is consistent with a diagnosis of acute cholecystitis. This is confirmed with the ultrasonographic findings of gallstones and a thickened gallbladder. Some degree of bile duct dilatation is very common in acute cholecystitis and does not necessarily imply choledocholithiasis. However, in this case, the patient does have abnormal liver function tests and whilst these would be consistent with acute cholecystitis, the possibility of duct pathology (stone) must be considered. In this case, as there is no evidence of CBD obstruction (normal bilirubin level) and no ductal stones identified on USS, \u003Cstrong\u003Emagnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be the recommended first line investigation. Whilst the best definition would be achieved with \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E, this is an invasive procedure and not without its own risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful investigative tool to assess diseases of the upper gastrointestinal tract and other nearby structures, it is also an invasive procedure and would not be the preferred initial imaging investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step to look at the biliary tree would be \u003Cstrong\u003Emagnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography.\u003C/strong\u003E This is a non-invasive imaging technique that provides good definition of the biliary and pancreatic ducts. It is particularly well-suited for identifying common duct stones and assessing the biliary tree without the need for contrast injection or invasive procedures. An example is shown, with a stone at the lower end of the common bile duct (Image). In cases where intervention may be required, MRCP can assist in preoperative planning by providing detailed information about the location and nature of the biliary obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EERCP\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that combines endoscopy and fluoroscopy to visualise and treat problems in the bile and pancreatic ducts. Whilst it can be therapeutic by allowing stone extraction, it is usually reserved for cases where intervention is needed, and its diagnostic use has decreased with the availability of non-invasive imaging like MRCP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHIDA scans\u003C/strong\u003E are useful for assessing gallbladder function and bile flow, but they may not provide detailed anatomical information about the cause of biliary obstruction. Given the need for a more direct visualisation of the bile ducts, MRCP is a more appropriate choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E CT scan of the abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful for assessing liver and surrounding structures. It is, however, not the first-line investigation for common duct stones and would not provide the detail that can be obtained with MRCP.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MRCP serves as the investigation of choice for confirming the suspected common duct stones.","To recognize the role of MRCP in the diagnostic pathway for obstructive jaundice, especially in situations where non-invasive and detailed evaluation of the biliary system is crucial for guiding appropriate management decisions."],"references":["Addley, J., Mitchell, R.M. Advances in the Investigation of Obstructive Jaundice. Curr Gastroenterol Rep 14, 511\u2013519 (2012). https://doi.org/10.1007/s11894-012-0285-1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84917"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12445"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20531"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20465"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20531"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bYZ4Ck7G4Q49XMzbZppf8fQcO9JM8T.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bYZ4Ck7G4Q49XMzbZppf8fQcO9JM8T.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":179}},{"type":"media","id":"20465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20465"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7X1NwTD6cvtfNV6ZUP3ov3MIkuY8ar.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7X1NwTD6cvtfNV6ZUP3ov3MIkuY8ar.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":633,"height":585}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84917"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T19:10:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T19:11:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4953"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102443"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"d